			<tr>
				<td class="PanelBodyAlternate"><span class="SmallBoldText">Re: use this song for lulling<a name="13645"/></span><br><span class="SmallText"> Posted: </span><span class="SmallText">Dec 23 03 9:32 AM</span></td>
			</tr><tr>
				<td colspan="2"><span> I'd have to agree with Calliope, LDoN is a rush job, people barely have time to wait for you to lull a mob-filled room, let alone bind-sight your way to it. Most people are understanding of the rush, so just do the best you can do, getting an add here and there is fine as long as you mezz it.
<br />

<br />
 If you're a bard puller, always have Lull and Mezz ready and always have your Sneak skill at hand. Pop on sneak when you open the doors if you're afraid of hiding mobs, it's a miracle worker. You can walk within &quot;you need a tic-tac&quot; distance to a mob without them noticing. Become accustomed to the limits of the skill and before you know it, you'll be lull/sneaking past half the dungeon to find those ellusive chests.
<br />

<br />
 With my LDoN spell set-up, I cant really spare an extra gem for yet another pulling song. I've 2 gems for pulling (lull and a tuyen chant), 4 for twisting (slow/snare, 2 hastes, 55 mana/health song), my mezz, and usually either Aria of Ascetism (for traps) or Brusco's Bumbostic Bellow.
<br />

<br />
 You're right that binding sight makes for a nice, smooth, possibly perfect pull. But perfection is not necessary, especially in LdoN.
<br />

<br />
 However, i found a good use for this song, pre-tracking levels. Enter a zone with groupmates, target them on the grouplist and you can bindsight with them whever they may be, helping you to locate those &quot;you outran me, come back&quot; people.
<br />

<br />
 I would be lying if i said this was an extremely useful song, but it has it's moments. One such use might be to scout something out, see a harmless rat scurrying past you, bind sight with the little fella and see what's ahead.
<br />

<br />
 Another note about this song, which makes it differant from every other song, this song resets target every tick. With most songs, the original target, when you start casting, is the target it will hit and keep hitting every tick, it is this system that allows you to keep one target infinatally mezzmarised whilst fighting a completely differant target.
<br />

<br />
 However, with SoV, if you're looking through someone's eyes and target something else, the Bind Sight will hop to the new target, next tick. This allows you to keep bouncing your vision from creature to creature as far as you want. Normally pretty useful feature.
<br />

<br />
 I've rambled enough, take care fellow bards.
<br />

<br />
</span></td>
			</tr><tr>
